< Text>
I‚Äôve had to take my son to the ER here twice and my daughter once.  The first time my son had split his forehead open.  We drove for an hour and then checked into emergency.  We went into triage and the nurse could see he was hurt but in good spirits and not bleeding substantially.  We waited for a couple minutes and were taken back to a room which was clean and had several people come in to decide between stitches and glue after he had a good cleaning and was checked out for a concussion or deep injuries.  After the cut was closed up, which seemed pretty much painless for him, we were sent on our way.  Overall a good experience and all staff was on point.
The second experience at Mad River Hospital was also pleasant.  We came into the ER to have our son and daughter looked at for a rash that popped up really quickly.  We were seen in triage  as soon as we walked in.  After waiting for 10-15 mins we were taken back to a room to have the kiddos checked out.  Several nurses came and checked them out to get a few opinions as there are a lot of unvaccinated people in the community and there were several possibilities as to what they thought could be wrong.  They decided to do a throat swab to check for strep and that‚Äôs what it turned out to be.  We don‚Äôt usually like to go to the ER for stuff like this but it would‚Äôve taken weeks to get an appointment somewhere else.  Both times we‚Äôve had to take our kids in the staff has been friendly and professional.  They made sure to take all the necessary steps to ensure our kids were getting the care they needed.  Recommended.< /Text>

<Date>1539806248896</Date><Response>None<//Response>< review>
There needs to be two reviews here, a five-star review for the nursing staff.  They were compassionate, sensitive to the indignities inherent in the procedure I was having, and they took outstanding care of me.

However, their billing department lacks competence, which could be costly if you don't know how to manage your own billing problems.  In January I had a screening test.  They billed it as if it were a diagnostic procedure.  The difference is clear, and very well spelled out in numerous sources.  One of those is the American Gastroenterological Association.  In my former life prior to grad school, I was a medical biller and know something about those codes and their uses.  In terms of direct effect on my wallet, they wanted over $800 they weren't owed.

The billing guidelines very clearly differentiate screening from diagnostic procedures, and the reimbursement differs between the two.  I figured it was a simple fix. Send them the guidelines, they'd fix the error.  After all,  not only are there numerous sources related to this common problem, but my insurance company and my physician agreed that the procedure was screening and not diagnostic.  Even after multiple letters to the billing department and the "patient experience officer", Mad River refused to re-bill, failed to provide their rationale for their billing, and threatened to send me to collections over the co-pay and deductible I didn't owe as those fees don't apply to preventative care.

I finally submitted an appeal directly to my insurance company to change the original billing, and they agreed. This is a common error, and one I assumed they'd correct once they were presented with the evidence.

If you are scheduled there for your middle-aged screening poke-n-prod,  know you're entitled to have that billed as preventative, which means you DO NOT OWE a deductible or co-pay with most insurance plans.  One way  you might be able to help yourself here is to make sure the word "screening" is written on the consent form for the procedure.<//review>

< text>
I won't lie, I was pleasantly surprised at my visit here! I've been to this place when it was under it's previous name; this week was my first visit to ICONIC Eats. Tuesday night after the dinner rush was pretty dead - my friend and I were the only ones here - this meant short wait for food ;) I got the beer battered portabella sandwich and my friend got the double craft burger. We were both very satisfied with our meals! Also split french fries, worth it. I got the double peanut butter shake - delish, didn't regret that. Service was awesome and attentive. This is a great spot for groups of varying diets - vegan, omnivore, keto, gluten free - all will be happy. The decor and atmosphere is pretty good. I'll be back and update as I try more dishes!< /text>

<gmapID>0x80c28712bff798d5:0x608243f7ac29ac7c<//gmapID><Review>Despite this place constantly changing either it's name or ownership, one thing they've kept constant, is the food; more specifically, their pizza. This little gem, tucked away in an already tucked away shopping center, will not disappoint someone looking to have actual quality pizza. Gone are the days in SCV where quality pizza is impossible to find and names like Tomato Joe's are tossed around as "the best". Write down the address of this place before it's name changes again, but trust in it's pizza because it will certainly not disappoint. As a little side note, the brussel sprouts appetizer is delicious. Vegetable lovers and haters alike, do yourself a favor and try them.< /Review></record>

<UserId.>105485183358150541786</UserId.><Name>Yasmine Zapp</Name><time>1527359346060< /time><rate>1< /rate>< Review>
We went their last Thursday for the first and last time. Despite the restaurant being nearly empty ( I counted 4 other tables) the service was beyond slow. Even getting a glass of water was a 10-15 min process. Ordering dinner was another 5 min after that. We we're casually informed an hour into our seating that the pizza chef had to leave (emergencies happen I know) and now anything involving bread, pizza, paninis, etc....we're off the menu. So we had to change our order...again.
Between the  4 of us we had 3 burgers and 1 sandwich (Bang Mi) in addition to a beer/glass of house wine, only one each. We waited so long(2 other tables waiting for food left) that our table was about to leave (purse in hand) when she brought our food. The burgers were dry and we asked for ketchup and mayo BOTH of which they were out of. Huh? The sandwich was beyond bland (tofu, cilantro mush) and our experience was just awful.
Then the bill came. We were shocked at how pricey it was ($125) and how (out of good faith) nothing was comped. My husband and I even spoke up about it to our waitress and she was no help and not willing to see the customer side of it. We paid cash, left a $10 tip and told her we would never be back. I am currently trying to contact the owner.
Honestly, I would of had more respect if they just shut the restaurant down for the night after the cook/chef left.</Review>

< Review>
Nick the Greek has great and quick Greek food that combines traditional dishes like Gyros with American ones like fries (Greek fries). I had the beef/lamb gyro, and although simple, it was delicious. For only $9.95, the meal was a very filling lunch that was fast. My order came out within 10 minutes and it was gone in five. This is a must have for people who stop by in Santa Cruz or just the bay area in general as I have seen other cities with them. Additionally, Nick the Greek was very spacious providing ample room for six feet. Along with this, staff wore masks and there were hand washing and sanitizing stations.< /Review>

< Review>
Tasty! Delicious! Eating here for the first time. Thanks to Covid, they got takeout and it couldn't have been smoother or quicker. I called in my order and by the time I got there, it was ready for me. Terrific set up for the times. Hand sanitizer by all entrances, telling patrons to use it and, of course, masks when entering. < text>
I actually really liked the Sunnyvale location of Nick's.  The food was fresh, servings large and the prices seemed reasonable.

This location our food was cold and the fries were overcooked and cold. An early problem we had hoped they had worked out.

I kept looking at their food prep video repeating over and over in front of me and thinking "I want THAT!"...not what I was served.  Those fries looked like what I got in Sunnyvale.

Music in the restaurant was really loud and pretty much precluded conversation.

Disappointed.</text>

< Text>
For my first time, Nick the Greek was fairly disappointing. We were here for the beginning of lunchtime and I expected everything to be cooked to order. Instead the fries were stale and dry. The feta cheese was not enough to make the Greek Fries worth the money.

For those of us that ordered meat, it was not the most pleasant experience, in that it lacked flavor, and it tasted a day old. When it came to the rice, it was crunchy, thus underdone.

We had researched the restaurant online. Watched some amazing videos of how the food is prepared and ultimately, we found ourselves disappointed in the quality of the food.</Text>

< Text>
Hands down the best Greek food in Santa Cruz. My wife and I ordered a couple of times through DoorDash and it always seems to arrive lukewarm. We remarked both times that we should try to go to the restaurant one time. I'm glad we did. It is so much better fresh out of the kitchen. I ordered my husband Rays 17 Hex Lug Nut and Lock Set from Evasive Motorsports. I was worried since we‚Äôve never ordered from here before but I decided to go through with it because they were decently priced compared to other places that I found online. I would definitely order from them again!<//Review>

Since January 2017 Molly Maids has cleaned our house every two weeks. The ladies (team) are reliable, dependable, and trustworthy. It takes a big burden off of me since I work everyday. Before I had started with Molly Maids, much of my weekends were spent cleaning house. So they have helped me to improve quality of life. A few weeks back we had a mis-hap and an heirloom wall clock was disturbed during the cleaning process. It fell, incurred some damage along with knocking out a light switch. Steve (Owner/Manager) came out the next day to survey the damage. He quickly arranged for a repairman to come out, pick up the clock and had it repaired. The man he hired brought the clock back and he did a fine job and you would never know that anything had happen to it. Steve fixed the light switch himself. All is well! Excellent Customer Service!!

Another point I would like to make is most recently we had an extended vacation. I was struggling with whom could take care of our cat while we were away. It was too long a time period to ask a neighbor to do it. I was looking at pet sitters, but I thought someone else (new) having to come into the house. Then it came to me, could Molly Maids come by an extra day or two to just give the cat water and make sure he had food?  I called the office, spoke with Kathy Gallegos. She  documented all of the details and asked her manager. We got the green light. But here's the good part! Kathy took it upon herself to come over after her shift, on her own time, to check on our cat and make sure he was OK. She even picked up our mail for us! I just can't say enough how pleased and grateful I am to Kathy and Molly Maids for this. They truly step up to please the customer in any way they can! Reliable, Friendly, Dependable, Trustworthy and Customer Focused! Thanks Kathy, Thanks Steve, Thanks to our team of ladies that cleans our house! You are all the best!</review>

< review>
This food was incredible! I will definitely be back. We came for a weekend trip and decided to have Sunday brunch on the warf. Best decision ever. The food presentation was artistic and Beautiful! The aroma was incredible. The smoked trout was to die for. It was smoothe and buttery in texture and the smoke on it was perfect. The crab bisque was creamy and had a smokey flavor to it which I loved.  The clams in the chowder were very tender and fresh which we enjoyed with the deliciousand fresh sourdough. My favorite dish however was the Salmon and crab cake Benedict. My eggs were cooked to perfection and the cake was the best I have ever had. There is definitely something to be said about eating fresh seafood right on the warf. The only thing that could have made my experience better would have been to watch the fishing boats unloading at the docks but it was Sunday. We did however get a lovely visit from a few Sea Lions. Couldn't have asked for a better experience on our trip.< /review>

Excellent quick service, I had a reservation but was able to be seated sooner than our appointed time. The food was fresh,not surprised since we are right by the water. Fried calamari had a perfect consistency of batter, texture and flavor. Amazing food. Friendly service.

My friend and I sat at the bar and had a marvelous experience. The bartender Kyler couldn't be friendlier. He recommended the right tequilas and meal.

<username>Asher McInerney< /username>< review>
A San Francisco institution that has adapted with the times. Kudos to Scoma‚Äôs for keeping the show going with great to go food and beverage. The out door dining options are really great now, especially if the weather is nice. The hosts, bartenders, wait staff and kitchen are all very kind and smiling. The food quality is really great and the prices are reasonable. Always fresh amazing g quality fish and seafood. The chowder and crab bisque are amazing. The calamari is a favorite. The sourdough is on point. Make sure to stop by especially if the weather is nice. Make a rez if you don‚Äôt want to wait but waiting around with a drink soaking in the scene ain‚Äôt so bad. Spicy margarita is excellent. Thanks!<//review>

Wonderful date place! With so many of the iconic restaurants in the heart of the tourist area closed I was lucky to find Scoma. Sat indoors in the dining room. It was intimate and well appointed. Service!  This was old world service. I can't remember the last time I had service this attentive to detail and my dining experience. The food was excellent. <user>104830388093091509737< /user><user_name>Joy</user_name>< Date>
1600844295713<//Date>
< rate>
4</rate>
< text>
It had been over six months since I had had a meal at a restaurant or made a reservation. With the sun shining, the idea of enjoying a cold crab salad overlooking the water appealed to me. Plus it's a nice image thinking of Al Scoma creating a family business 50+ years ago and having a pier named after him. Could such a story unfold for a scrappy go-getter these days?

We were a few minutes early for our lunch reservation, so we took the time to enjoy the view of the water and the mosaic ode to the city outside. Definitely easy to appreciate on a warm day. A few minutes later, we were seated at a picnic style table and received sourdough bread and whipped butter, and glasses of ice water.

Unfortunately, one of the glasses had remnants of red lipstick on it. We brought it to our server's attention, and later on, he replaced our water. Without a word, he took the glass and walked away. I couldn't help thinking it would have been nice if he had shown some sign of remorse. I understand that dishwashers can leave behind residue, but given these especially germaphobic times, a little sign of concern for the patrons from the staff goes a long way.

$13 Crab Bisque Bowl:
This orange bowl had a creamy tomato flavor with chunks of crab meat, topped with chives and cracked pepper.

$21 Scoma's Dungeness Crab Cake:
A pair of lightly battered and fried crab medallions were served with a small portion of arugula salad on the side and some creamy dipping salad. The crab was still chunky, which was definitely a plus, because that definitely beats crab cakes with pulverized crab mush.

$47 Scoma's Crab Louis Salad "Classic" 1/2 lb:
I knew the Crab Louis was going to be a large portion, even with the smaller "Classic" sized portion, but when I saw the plate set down in front of me, I knew we would have leftovers. The pile of crab meat sat on top of shredded lettuce, decked out with juicy heirloom tomatoes, cucumber slices, a boiled egg, bell peppers, carrots, olives, lemon wedges, and a ramekin overflowing with Louis dressing. It was cool and refreshing, not to mention the crab and the accoutrements were sweet and satisfying. My only complaint was I would have preferred if the carrot were peeled, because the outer layers looked a touch hairy.
I happily packed up the leftovers and looked forward to digging into it for my next meal. Our server joked that we did a good effort, but ate too much of the salad, haha.

I thoroughly enjoyed the food, and I probably would have enjoyed it even more if I had the opportunity to witness seeing the 'Pier to Plate' process unfold. I would rate my experience a 7/10, and would be more of a solid 4/5 had it not been for the dirty glasses. I wish I could say that I will save myself the money and make my own Crab Louis, but I sure do appreciate someone else shelling all that crab.< /text>

<userid>107301438362214008475<//userid><user_name>Isabelle Tran<//user_name><Date>1545531470238</Date><rating>4< /rating>< Review>
Came for lunch and enjoyed it. They serve a good range of Italian and seafood dishes.

Seafood was fresh. Pasta was ok tasting but came in huge portions - if you are a small eater, one between two people is enough. Clam chowder was delicious.

Service was great. The seating was a bit small so it was not that comfortable.</Review>

< user>
101531930998111061143<//user>
<user_name>Keith Brown< /user_name><Date>1535857269580< /Date><Rating>5<//Rating>< Review>
A great restaurant a little off the beaten path on Fisherman's Wharf. That is they own their own boats and seafood processing facility across the street. Excellent seafood prepared extremely well! By the way they also make craft cocktails including a Bloody Mary made with house made gin. There are so many places to choose from but even at lunch hour in the middle of the week, this restaurant is very busy. Scoma's was recommended by our cabbie a lifelong resident of San Francisco. Locals surely know it and we were happy that we followed his advice.</Review>

Delicious Fish n Chips!  The batter is made the traditional way. The food is made fresh by order. The portions are generous. My daughter and I shared one order and it was plenty to eat.

Picnic tables are available for seating in front.

This place is a nice addition to the Fisherman's Wharf eateries!</Text>

< review>
We were in seafood heaven! Both the seafood entree and mains were mouth-watering and divine. We couldn't get enough! They matched well with a local chardonnay and the Pisco Punch cocktail. To top it off we had the delicious tiramisu. It was a perfect evening at Scoma's - delightful ambience with excellent and attentive service. Hands down the best meal we had on this trip!
Tip: Make a reservation to avoid waiting for a table (even on a week night) as this place is very busy.</review>

<username>Cathy Perez<//username><time>1557790901617</time><rating>5< /rating>< Review>
A friend suggested this restaurant to me and I'm so glad she did! First of all, the staff was amazing. They were very friendly and, helpful with suggestions.
Had an amazing margarita to start and had the trio for 2 as an appetizer which includes, calamari, crabcakes and bacon wrapped scallops. Now I am usually not a fan of seafood beyond calamari but the crabcakes were amazing and came with a delicious dipping sauce. Also had a delicious caesar salad.
I had the filet as an entree with asparagus with lemon and it was cooked perfectly and tasted delicious. One of the best dinners I've had in quite a while.<//Review>

< Review>
Very fresh seafood that they say is sourced from the local fishermen and fisheries. They're generous with the butter and everything is consistent. The first time I came here, I had the louie salad, which was extremely basic. My latest return I tried out their seafood pastas and it was so rich I could die. Definitely something you need lots of bread for, but worth trying. Interior is a little bit nautical and storied with the waiters being attentive and checking in often. It's a bit on a the pricier side, but worth the price.<//Review>

<date>1590930633726</date>< Review>
Everything is fantastic at Scoma's. This is a must if you are in San Francisco, excellent Clam chowder, Caesar salad, and freshest sea food you can get. We love it here, family favorite!

Easy to walk to. It's tucked away from the per noise. The atmosphere reminded me of old San Francisco, dark wood, nice comfy bar stools.

The food and service was Great. And they were able to accommodate the large party of diners that were in attendance with us. Definitely recommend reservations. The food was excellent, the wine selection was superb, and the service was efficient and professional. Highly recommend.< /Review>

< review>
On a work trip after a full day. We ate dinner here. It was one of the few dining options available to get us out of our hotel room.

They had extra tables setup where parking used to be. So we ate outside. The view was awesome. The service was top notch.

Drinks. Delicious. I had the smoked maple old fashioned. My dining mate (and friend and coworker) had a Southern Comfort and 7up.

Dinner (we couldn't fit dessert) was the grilled king salmon over Scomaronia and the Cioppino.

We ordered a couple apps too. Dungeness crab, oysters and shrimp. All good. All gone.

We so enjoyed our dinner here!

Thank you team Scoma!!

Hopefully you are able to get a new boat soon!!<//review>

< Review>
I was looking for a nice place to eat on the bay, but the restaurants on Fisherman's Wharf looked way too touristic to me. I opted for this more hidden restaurant and I've been positively surprised. First, the staff is super friendly and welcoming. Then the atmosphere, very "marine" with all the wood. Last but not least, the food is great! Fresh fish from the bay, with many different options available. Wasn't expecting this quality. Sure, is not the cheapest option around, but if you want to eat well this i's the place to go!<//Review>

< Review>
I would give this place NO STARS if the site would let me!

Up until tonight, I always loved this place. In fact, I had made a commitment to patronize local restaurants that remained open during the Shelter in Place order to help them during this crisis. Scoma's was one of those places. I had ordered "curbside delivery" a couple of times, no problem. Drive up, someone comes out, takes your card, goes inside and runs the check, and then comes right back with your bill to sign and your bag of food. And away you go. I might add that the service was always masked and gloved.

So tonight, I called in an order, arrived in my car at the time I said I would be there. Someone was there to tell me where to park, and there I sat with absolutely no acknowledgement from the staff inside for the next 15 minutes! Meanwhile, there was a birthday party going on right in front of me, and they received two full food deliveries while I was sitting there!

The same parking guy walked by again and I finally got his attention. He went in to check on my order, and a girl came and informed me that I had to COME INSIDE AND PAY to get my order - OH REALLY? SINCE WHEN? What happened to the "curbside delivery" that you have advertised on your website, and that I've patronized at least twice without any problem? She then informed me that it was because I called my order in rather than ordering online - RIGHT! I called my orders before without any problems, so I knew that wasn't it. She finally admitted that they were busy - evidently too busy to handle the transaction as advertised. OK, well then I'm too busy to be your customer! I told her to skip it and drove away without my order.

So this is how you treat your neighborhood patrons who were loyal to you during the SIP? Suddenly the SIP order's relaxed and  you're letting people into your restaurant to order and pay, and people are standing around in the parking lot, less than six feet apart and no masks, partying and getting all your service. I see. And now I hope some of my neighbors will see, too. SHAME ON YOU. If that's how you're going to treat loyal customers, then you will never get my business again. SHAME. ON. YOU!<//Review>
<pictures>None<//pictures><Response>{'time': 1592259196011, 'text': "Hi Stefanie. Thank you so much for your kind words on always loving us and we greatly appreciate your efforts to support us during the SIP. We looked into what happened there and unfortunately it was a perfect storm of getting slammed and not having the proper training for the staff that was on hand at the time. We do happily offer curbside service and do handle the transactions as advertised. It will not happen again. Next time you order or come by, please introduce yourself so we can apologize in person and make sure you have a 100% perfect experience. Thank you and we look forward to serving you again."}<//Response><gmapID>0x808580fc871ec6ad:0x976bca61020dcc34< /gmapID></record></dataset><record>

<user>110379102758240490875<//user><name>Catherine Vasquez</name><date>1592067396032<//date><Rating>1</Rating><review>This restaurant shares the pier with fishing boats (that also pay rent) and park here so that we can all get fresh fish. It's a pier after all. Now they want to stop the boats from being there and that's very unfair. These are hard times for everyone we all need to innovate and yes they might need some more outdoor space but also be reasonable and share. I would like to hear a reasonable explanation from the new management.<//review><Pictures>None</Pictures><Response>{'time': 1592089091527, 'text': 'Catherine, please know Scoma\'s is perhaps the biggest supporter of the local fishing fleet in the entire city. We are more than happy to have any fishing boat being on the pier and several do. We have been letting FV Pioneer sell seafood in our parking lot, which we pay for, at no cost to them. We have no ability, desire or authority to put anyone out of business, and the Pioneer could easily move to a different slip if it wanted to.\n\nIt is an unfortunate situation but we have well over 100 employees, many local fishing crews and countless farmers whose livelihoods depend on our being able to conduct business. After offering several solutions to the FV Pioneer no agreement could be reached.\n\nPlease read this unbiased statement from the Port of San Francisco if you are interested in knowing the facts of the situation.\n\nThank you for your feedback we we hope this response and the Port\'s statement below gives you clarity on the situation.\n\nStatement issued by the Port of San Francisco yesterday:\n\n"This is a COVID-19 public safety issue now that Scoma‚Äôs can offer outdoor dining on their leasehold. Moreover, FV Pioneer has no claim to operate retail fish sales on property that Scoma‚Äôs leases.\n\nScoma‚Äôs voluntarily agreed to allow a portion of their leasehold to be temporarily used since 2017 without costs to FV Pioneer for retail fish sales as a good neighbor supporting local fishers. Otherwise, the FV Pioneer would not have been able to operate a fish retail business without the cooperation of Scoma‚Äôs and the Port.\n\nScoma‚Äôs can no longer accommodate FV Pioneer retail fish sales on its property due to health and social distancing guidelines. The City has offered new opportunities for restaurants, whose doors have been shuttered for the past three months, to operate outdoor dining in efforts to stem the financial hardship that the virus has caused on the restaurant industry.\n\nScoma‚Äôs and FV Pioneer attempted to work together to find a mutually beneficial solution. As no solution has presented itself, the Port must support Scoma‚Äôs claims to use the property they are leasing from the Port. Thus, the FV Pioneer can berth there but it may no longer make retail sales."\n\nFor additional information please contact the Port of San Francisco Public Affairs Office.'}< /Response><gmapID>0x808580fc871ec6ad:0x976bca61020dcc34< /gmapID></record></dataset><record>
< user>
110661951617374454080< /user>
<Date>1582507558976</Date><Resp>None<//Resp><review>I'm a local, and I eat on the San Francisco waterfront often. This is definitely one of the best meals I've had near the Pier 39 / fisherman's wharf area.

Fried calamari was very good, although it could have been just a touch more crispy.

Crispy fries with truffle oil and parmesan cheese were out of this world.

The beet salad was small for the price, but tasted amazing.

The bread roll tasted fresh, but it was not warm.

Service was fast and friendly. I was dining alone and I got one of the tables facing out toward the fishing boats.

The location makes this one of those places that you will not stumble onto. You must see the sign and walk toward the Bay down the pier.

The restaurant is like time stopped in 1965, but it's clean and well-maintained inside.

food is expensive, but not over-the-top expensive. I ordered three appetizers, calamari, crispy fries, and the beet salad. And with two diet Pepsi's it came to $51, before tip.

I will definitely be back here.<//review><Pictures>None</Pictures><GmapID>0x808580fc871ec6ad:0x976bca61020dcc34<//GmapID>< rate>

In my opinion this has to be one of the best restaurants in the US. Tucked away down a small street at Fisherman's Wharf in San Francisco, Scoma's is like finding buried treasure. The restaurant itself is not overly ostentatious but the warm friendly staff make you feel imediately welcome.

I have to say, this was the best chicken pasta dish I have ever tasted. It was sublime. Its no surprise, whereever you look that this particular restaurant has reviews of 4.5 stars and over. My rating is a full 5* and that it is my number 1 restaurant in the US so far. If you are ever in the area don't miss an opportunity to pay Scoma's a visit.< /Review>

<text>Before going on our honeymoon, we were told by several people that all the places to eat at or around fisherman's wharf are essentially the same...while that isn't a bad thing, the sole exception is Scoma's. While all the seafood around the wharf is likely fresh, at Scoma's not only do you know it is but the service and preparation they put into each meal is unmatched. Our server dutifully told us exactly which dishes were locally caught and prepared fresh vs frozen. I started with the clam chowder and can honestly say it was one of the best I ever had. For entrees, my wife and I had the locally caught, fresh blackened cod.  Perfectly cooked and spiced, it was so good, I had to slow myself down to enjoy it more...as well as stop myself from just going caveman on it and eating it with my bare hands. Also, as a bonus, our awesome waiter (who had previously asked what brought us to San Fran after learning that we lived in NJ) brought us some incredible sorbet and ice cream to congratulate us on our marriage/honeymoon. This added an entire new level to our experience. When we are in San Fran again, we will definitely be returning!< /text><resp>None</resp><Name>Kevin Grim< /Name></record>

< Text>
Three is being generous. Traveling in San Francisco and Scoma's was highly recommended by our hotel staff and the glowing Google reviews. Our waiter, Timothy was less than interested in us as customers, not helpful in advising us on menu selections and overall, just a dud.  We should have asked to change to the waiter people nearby had- he was outgoing, knowledgeable and sold the menu items with skill and was not pushy. As for our entrees, my shrimp and scallops were OK, my client got the mixed grill which was over cooked and on a par with hotel banquet fare. Dessert was limited, and the tiramisu was suspiciously like what Olive Garden served. For nearly $200, this was disappointing. The salmon mac and cheese was actually great, so possibly I should have settled for this and a salad. We did enjoy the location and decor, and might (?) give Scoma's another try, with the hope this was just an "off" evening.< /Text>

<Text>Let me start by saying coming from NY especially near many Italian and seafood inspired places I came in with very high expectations.  Although the food was good by many standards, it was not WOW.  Typical seafood fare, and flare.  Service was fast, courteous, and prices were what one would expect for the area and for seafood.  I had a plate of pasta and assorted seafood.  Seafood was fresh tasting and the pasta was good.  I also has a cup of the crab bisque which was very rich and filling- the highlight of the night.  My fiance had a grilled platter of assorted fish- which was light, flaky but nothing to rave about.  All in all, if you're in the mood for seafood I would recommend Scoma.  However, if you're in the mood for dishes incorporating seafood to set a new bar- I'd say try somewhere else.</Text>< Pictures>

< review>
I don‚Äôt dish out 5-star reviews often but this place deserved it. Incredible food and excellent service. As someone who comes from Europe and struggles with huge American portions, this place was reasonable when we ordered an appetiser to share and a starter each (came to about regular European portions). Recommend crab cakes - you get two with a little side salad/generous garnish, and the clam chowder (go for a bowl rather than a cup for a European ‚Äòmain‚Äô size) and crab bisque.

Delicious, fresh, excellent! Usually recommended to reserve, we got lucky and walked in without a reservation. But a place this good will be busy - so either reserve or be prepared for a wait - it is worth it tho.<//review>

The crab bisque to start was outstanding. It was downhill from there. Shell bits in my crab cocktail. Shrimp was slightly over for main course but the scallops were perfect. Plating and vegetables with the main, straight from 1965 when they opened. Wait staff? All from 1965 too I think. {'time': 1592014141885, 'text': 'Vol, it seems like you are referring to the issue FV Pioneer has brought up. Please know Scoma\'s has long been one of, if not the biggest supporters of the local fishing fleet, including FV Pioneer. Below is a statement from the Port of San Francisco outlining the facts of the situation:\n\n"This is a COVID-19 public safety issue now that Scoma‚Äôs can offer outdoor dining on their leasehold. Moreover, FV Pioneer has no claim to operate retail fish sales on property that Scoma‚Äôs leases.\nScoma‚Äôs voluntarily agreed to allow a portion of their leasehold to be temporarily used since 2017 without costs to FV Pioneer for retail fish sales as a good neighbor supporting local fishers. Otherwise, the FV Pioneer would not have been able to operate a fish retail business without the cooperation of Scoma‚Äôs and the Port.\nScoma‚Äôs can no longer accommodate FV Pioneer retail fish sales on its property due to health and social distancing guidelines. The City has offered new opportunities for restaurants, whose doors have been shuttered for the past three months, to operate outdoor dining in efforts to stem the financial hardship that the virus has caused on the restaurant industry.\nScoma‚Äôs and FV Pioneer attempted to work together to find a mutually beneficial solution. As no solution has presented itself, the Port must support Scoma‚Äôs claims to use the property they are leasing from the Port. Thus, the FV Pioneer can berth there but it may no longer make retail sales."\n\nThank you for your interest and please contact the Port of San Francisco if you have any questions regarding this situation.'}< /response>

I was conducting my San Francisco Photo Tours for my Florida clients and a Lyft Driver recommended Scoma's for the best clam chowder in San Francisco. The restaurant was hard to find but we finally found it. Service was real slow when we arrive like 9 pm. It was busy and we finally got our clam chowder. Lots of black/white celebrity photos on the wall. And also the Bar area was really nice and quiet and luxurious.  This place has history and prices are $$$ so be sure to have at least $ 100 in your wallet. It's worth a visit on your next trip to San Francisco<//Text>

< Review>
We have been coming to Scomas for decades. We moved away from CA to N. Carolina, so we came to eat on a visit back. The food was fantastic and our service was impeccable as always. We asked for special orders from the old menu, which they made for us. I am glad they are now committed to sustainability, but the prices had gone up a lot and the portion sizes have gone down. The price increase, along with the smaller portions is the reason for 4 stars rather than 5. I can see one or the other, but not both. The price increase for the seafood saute was 30%!< /Review>

<name>Elle G<//name><Date>1566235292888<//Date><rating>4</rating>< Review>
I was conducting my San Francisco Photo Tours for my Florida clients and a Lyft Driver recommended Scoma's for the best clam chowder in San Francisco. The restaurant was hard to find but we finally found it. Service was real slow when we arrive like 9 pm. It was busy and we finally got our clam chowder. Lots of black/white celebrity photos on the wall. And also the Bar area was really nice and quiet and luxurious.  This place has history and prices are $$$ so be sure to have at least $ 100 in your wallet. It's worth a visit on your next trip to San Francisco</Review>

< Text>
I'm genuinely confused by how highly rated this is. Even for the fisherman's wharf or Pier 39, the food was pretty terrible. The clam chowder was alright if you could overcome the grittiness of what I assumed was poorly cleaned clams. I will say that the truffle fries were good, but slightly oily. I got the petrale dore, which was recommended by our waiter, and it was absolutely horrible. I would not recommend this dish unless you like to pay $35 for oily, deep fried cardboard. The only redeeming thing on the plate was the tartar sauce, but that wasn't enough to cover the horrendous taste of the petrale. When I told the staff who took my staff that I didn't want leftovers a sit was just not good, nothing was done about it. Seriously, make the trek to Woodhouse, Waterbar, or anywhere on the grotto if you want good seafood.< /Text>

< review>
We found this famous gem of an eatery tucked away behind the gaudier offerings on the main drag. It lived up to its reputation. This was some of the best food we had had on our vacation. There are no chowders in bread bowls here. Only delicious, no-nonsense local fish dishes. The children‚Äôs meal was fantastic since it included not just fish and fries but also greens and carrots!  And, what‚Äôs more, it was served on an actual plate! (Unlike many children's meals.) It‚Äôs not cheap but it‚Äôs much better value than some other local restaurants. Would very highly recommend.<//review>

104592558160789607417< /UserId.>
<gmap_id>0x808580fc871ec6ad:0x976bca61020dcc34< /gmap_id><rating>1<//rating>< Review>
I'm genuinely confused by how highly rated this is. Even for the fisherman's wharf or Pier 39, the food was pretty terrible. The clam chowder was alright if you could overcome the grittiness of what I assumed was poorly cleaned clams. I will say that the truffle fries were good, but slightly oily. I got the petrale dore, which was recommended by our waiter, and it was absolutely horrible. I would not recommend this dish unless you like to pay $35 for oily, deep fried cardboard. The only redeeming thing on the plate was the tartar sauce, but that wasn't enough to cover the horrendous taste of the petrale. When I told the staff who took my staff that I didn't want leftovers a sit was just not good, nothing was done about it. Seriously, make the trek to Woodhouse, Waterbar, or anywhere on the grotto if you want good seafood.< /Review>

1416592459381</Time>
<Rate>5<//Rate>< Text>
I visited in June of 2014. It took me a bit to get past the dated decor...

It was a little hard for a first timer to San Francisco to find, but turned out to be a hidden gem.

The food was absolutely out of this world. Dishes were spot on. Some of the best and freshest seafood I have tasted anywhere. Pasta was cooked perfectly (not over done like most places will serve).  Sauces tasted fresh.

This was the first restaurant I visited on my first visit to San Francisco, and it set the bar high for my expectations of the quality of seafood for the area. Some restaurants came close but none matched.

I would highly recommend this restaurant!</Text>

<text>I was taken to this restaurant for my anniversary.  Believe me when I say I tried to get out of it.  I didn't want to sit in a restaurant that smelled of fish or had creatures swimming awaiting their doom.  So I balked all the way to San Francisco.  When we arrived I thought it's a "Hole in the Wall" from the area we had driven into.  Then a valet came to park the car which I found odd because the restaurant appeared very small from the outside.
Boy, was I fooled.

Inside, you have a reservation counter and a cozy waiting place upstairs with vintage pictures on the wall.  There may be a 30 - 45 minute wait but you are not uncomfortable.  Drinks may be ordered from the waiting area and it's not drafty.  Upon going to the dining room, the doors were slid back and what a view!  Elegant dining room with a back wall view of the bay.  Service was on point and at the time Walter was my server.  He was the most charming man ever.  I had the Lobster Provolone Dinner and it was hands-down 5 star!  We had a Lovely evening.

Two weeks later in-laws from Germany arrived and after hearing about Scoma's took us out to this restaurant.  We all had a delightful time and this is now my favorite restaurant.  The crab salad is a must!  One salad fed 4 adults and we were almost too full for the meal.  Excellent!  10 Star!!</text><Date>1520787517942</Date>< resp>

<username>Julia Lloyd-Cowden< /username>< text>
Nothing was particularly wrong, but nothing was spectacular either. We tried Scoma's based on several recommendations by friends. Our waitress was great, very attentive and knowledgeable about the menu. We order drinks to start while deciding what to eat, the drinks were delivered quickly, they're fine...a little light on the alcohol based on how much they're charging and not made as well as other places. We order an appetizer to split and order our entrees at the same time. Our appetizer never comes... It ends up being delivered with our entrees. Not what we wanted with an appetizer but ok. I order the cioppino, and it was tasty. He orders the steak (doesn't like seafood), and it's just ok... The steak was cooked well enough but not great, the parmesan polenta was not very good (I've made better at home) and the mushrooms were just ok (he didn't like the texture of how they were cooked). We decide on dessert, our waitress expounds on how great their pastry chef is.... It's a lie, the desserts were no better than grocery store bought desserts. Overall a disappointment based on recommendations and reviews, and their own reporting.</text>

<review>We have a tradition of eating lunch at Scoma's when we fly in to San Fran from the east coast.  It's our first stop. <review>This place is incredible .
I don't really like seafood but I loved every single thing I ate (& I even ate a tentacle!). My other half loved seafood and loved it too.The food is fantastic and there is a lovely atmosphere.
There's a classy 60s feel inside (the waiters are in white jackets and  and just so lovely and knowledgeable). Scoma have their own boat and you can literally watch the fish come off the boat, into their processing plant and into the restaurant. You can't get fresher.
Don't let the lack of outdoor seating put you off. We arrived at sunset on a lovely night & wanted to sit outside ...... But actually a seat in the lounge by the window was incredible. We watched a lovely sunset and kept warm.< /review><pictures>None<//pictures>< Resp>

< Text>
My sister and I has a late dinner here tonight. We added ourselves to the handy yelp waitlist at 8:00pm and were 17th in line.  We were instructed to be at the restaurant at 8:30pm.

We arrived late because or lyft driver was very slow but they still honored our waitlist spot.  We had a very professional and attentive waiter but not extremely personable.  I ordered the 3 fish grill (cod, salmon and halibut) and a cup of clam chowder. I loved the halibut and the salmon was above average the cold tasted a teeny bit underdone but that may have been the texture since it is a flaky fish.  She ordered calamari app, ceasar salad and a cup of clam chowder. She enjoyed everything as well but we both agreed the clam chowder was the belle of the ball.

It was a pricey meal at nearly a hundred dollars for our meals but it was a prime location and beautiful post sunset view.

While I wouldn't insist on a revisit, I have no regrets.  It was a lovely meal and a great experience.< /Text>

< review>
I've been coming to Scoma's since around 1984 and I've always loved it.  The view, the vibe, the food.  The clam chowder is great, it's the first place I ever had fried calamari (with marinara, pls) but the cioppino is my absolute favorite.  I couldn't visit SF without visiting Scoma's.</review>

< review>
It's been years since we have gone to Scoma's. They had the best Ciopino I had ever had, so really looking forward to the meal. I didn't mind the 90 minute wait, because of the tremendous food. <Review>There were 2 sides to our experience.  First we went at 2:30pm and it was very busy, unfortunately they couldn't handle it.  We had a very efficient guy filling up our drinks and bringing us bread but that wasn't the waiter, the waiter took a long, long time to take our orders, even though we had told the drink-server guy we were ready ages before.  He also made an excuse rather than just apologizing.  Then my wife was brought her chowder way before my scampi starter, this is just amateur.  Then our mains were brought before our starters had been taken away, not such a bad thing but it's a clear indication of a badly run floor and pass.  The food was tasty but also expensive.  The table next to us had complained that one of their dishes tasted very strange although the chef did come over and apologize.  Overall it was great food with very badly organized service. <Review>Hidden behind Fisherman's Wharf with a view of the water this place is worth the few extra steps and sometimes short wait.  Once you are seated you are greeted by the most friendly staff and walked through the delicious daily specials(many of them right off the boat).  They have a nice wine menu and you are given a nice basket of bread to munch on while your food is being prepared.

A little bit pricey, but well worth it compared to the other tourists traps around the Wharf this place is worth the money.  The Cioppino is to die for and comes in a huge portion, The fresh swordfish is also a favorite menu item.</Review>< pics>

< UserId.>
106041334903107118605<//UserId.>
< Review>
The best possible seafood in San Francisco. Scomas is a landmark in Fisherman's wharf. They have the freshest seafood, right off the boat. Beautiful views day or night. The bay is lapping right up to the parking lot - and yes, they have free parking, just remember to tip the hard working valets. They can have long waits to be seated, you're welcome to call ahead and ask what the wait time is. The long waits to be seated are because they are the best seafood restaurant ever. People come from all over the world to eat at Scoma's.
Try it.  You won't be disappointed.< /Review>

< Text>
Lovely place to eat! My wife and I were in San Francisco above the Fisherman's Wharf area from July 1 - 5, 2002, shortly after our marriage, and a nearby shopkeeper (would that I could remember his name or of his store!) recommended Scoma's as a great place to eat. He was right. Fantastic food and service. My one disappointment was trying Dungeness Crab but aside from that, nothing whatsoever to complain about. I can't wait to come back and enjoy the fine food and drink Scoma's has to offer. P.S. You do have Alaskan King Crab legs don't you?  ;)<//Text>

< Review>
Oh my! What a find!   We were near Fisherman's Warf looking for a good bite to eat and Yelp suggested this place.   When we walked in I was a little worried that we were underdressed because the wait staff was bow ties and sharp as could be.  But I figured, "meh, my money's green."
Our waiter was very kind and kept our kids supplied with a delicious crusty bread. We barely scratched the menu but the fish and chips and clam chowder were absolutely excellent.  I for one am pretty hard to please with those two items and Scoma's nailed them.
Overall our lunch in SanFran was one of the best experiences of the trip.< /Review>

I had the Classic Crab Louie Salad (~$40). The crab was tasteless. I ate about 1/3 and gave up. Server assured me it was not frozen, but the lack of taste suggested to me it probably canned. Server suggested they may have 'washed' the crab reducing the flavor?

My friend had the Poor Man's Cioppino (~$40), which was an apt description. Lots of seafood in a thick sauce that could have been V8 juice. The brussel sprouts($9) were very good, you can't really go wrong when you add bacon to anything. Tasty bread and butter. Definitely a tourist trap, would not recommend.

Total bill a bottle of sparkling water ~$107, no alcohol. Yes, we could have sent it all back and walked out, some days you just don't have the energy for that.

Tonight we have reservations at 'Dirty Habit' and much higher expectations.< /text>

< pics>
None< /pics>
< Review>
Love this place! Very fresh seafood, very tasty. Love the mafioso appeal. The walls filled with countless autographed celebrity photos offer amusing eye appetizers while awaiting our entrees. Best clam chowder I've ever had in The City. It's a little hidden but in a good way, likely keeping out wandering tourists or weekend hippies from chancing upon it, making it next to impossible to get a window table on a walk-in. Of all of the many eateries around San Francisco's great Wharf, Scoma's is the the only one I personally consider worthy of historical significance. Yes, Boudins began here and may still be the more popular restaurant even today, however in my opinion Boudins has grown into the Budweiser of bread. Scoma's has something no other Embarcadero restaurant has, a pulse, an identity, character, and bay city charm.  Stepping into Scoma's feels like stepping out of the city. A peaceful, quiet, sense will greet you as you enter as if time itself slows. Forwarding through time, neighboring eateries will likely fade away while Scoma's remains, gaining fame, iconic status, and historical importance. What Randy's Donuts is to LA, or what Katz Delicatessen is to Manhattan, so should Scoma's be to SF. From the cresting waves of the mighty Pacific Ocean, along California's golden coastline, a small port town filling with migrant ruffians and Forty-Niners quickly grew outward and upward. It grew across steep terrain, eventually gaining root spanning the entire Southern Peninsula. Where Giant Pacific Redwood forests once grew, now grows a mighty metropolis. A civilization so grand that Westerners know simply as, "The City," and it was here, hidden down a narrow alleyway, treaded upon by those who've come to know of it. There, built directly onto the wooden planks of a dock, nearest the point where city becomes sea, that is where you'll find it...  Scoma's. To all you soon to be first timers, you're welcome.</Review>

< Pictures>
None<//Pictures>
<user>104607424381319946855</user>< Review>
Started with a perfect Bloody Mary while waiting 45 minutes for a table.  Never has a wait been so worth it!

We had a bowl of clam chowder.  Fresh clams and organic ingredients. It was far and away the best I have had!

The entre was Pasta Diplomatica which is sort of an Alfredo white sauce.  Fresh ground pepper and fresh grated cheese added to the mix. It was a huge portion of one of the best entre's I have ever had!  Simply delicious!

The wait staff, of which there are plenty, are always there before you need them.  Always filling glasses or taking care of things, but never intruding into the meal.

It was the best meal I have had in a very long time!  Only shame was we had no room for desert.  And the desert menu was sooo tempting.

I will never come to San Francisco and miss Scoma's restaurant!< /Review>

<Rate>2< /Rate>< Review>
If you think Olive Garden is fancy, then you're in for a treat.
Every thing about Scoma's is dated and out of style but screams a desperate attempt at the appearance of class. Wood paneling, conference room seating and walls of photographs of celebrities no one under 40 can name.
The food was fresh and edible, but the dishes are the very definition of boring and poorly executed by what I assume are novice chefs.
The waitstaff are, from my experience, old, slow, dressed in the typical steak house white jacket/black pants and walk with a sad, hunched, shuffling gait.
Scoma's antiquity would be endearing, if the food were not so painfully boring.<//Review>

<Rate>4</Rate><Text>Popped in right before they were closing to grab a couple glasses of wine and some calamari. Best part of the evening is the fact we were driven here in a brand new Bentley flying spur, which was awesome, so it began with us leaving AT&T park after watching USC crush CAL (Fight On), so we proceeded to try and catch a cab, but with no luck we walked down to the  St. Regis to catch a drink and instead were greeted by the doormen offering the house car for a tour of San Francisco. We accepted.
The driver opened the doors to the beautiful car, we got in, and drove us all over the city showing us different sites and telling us a little history about each location, while my fiance and I sat in back worried that we smelled funny after our rooftop tailgate before the game with friends, but he didn't seem to notice, and we certainly weren't going to bring it up.
After he took us to a few wine bars he inquired about our lust for seafood and asked if he could suggest a spot, so we obliged and he took us to Scoma, but not before making sure a table was ready for us. We arrived and were greeted by an amazing staff and enjoyed some great bites to eat while sipping a fantastic Malbec.
The long and short of it is this, we had a great evening with great food and wine, which cannot be beat by much.</Text>< Pics>

<UserId.>101061380552119050396</UserId.>< Name>
Steve Pendleton<//Name>
< Time>
1294347651536< /Time>
<rate>3<//rate>< Text>
This is an old restaurant that is trying to be old-style elegant. It isn't anything but old style anymore. Yes, the waiters wear white jackets, but the paneling in the dining room just looks...old. The prices are high, even for Fisherman's Wharf. Typical entree is $30+. The service is not excellent. When we arrived it was a very light Monday night crowd, but the hostess would not seat us until our friend who was parking the car arrived five minutes later. When you are really busy I can see this, but not if the restaurant is more than half empty. The quality of the food is mixed. My wife had lamb chops. Two were excellent, one was raw...and tasteless. I had swordfish in a picatta sauce. The fish was excellent, but the sauce was thin. Bottomline: there are better seafood restaurants at Fisherman's Wharf.<//Text>

<date>1517080810202< /date><Name>Ashley Thoren< /Name><Gmap_id>0x808580fc871ec6ad:0x976bca61020dcc34< /Gmap_id>< resp>
None< /resp>
<pictures>None</pictures><user>105085349535444602120<//user>< rating>
4< /rating>
< Review>
Scoma's is a legacy, but they are just fundamentally being outgrown. Wish they would pare down the menu, update the decor a little bit, and put a little more attention on the waitstaff's skills.

Service was good, appropriately polite and attentive, but kind of clumsy in execution for the intended ambience. E.g. reaching over other guests to serve plates and grate cheese, or forgetting which plate goes where, or just generally awkward interruptions in table conversation and rushed ordering. To be fair, we sat at the bar tables instead of waiting for our reservation.

Food was good but not great. My Bolognese was obviously fresh but the papardelle was sticking and the sauce wasn't much to write home about. Table bread was cold.

I recognize that I'm likely being picky on the details, but based upon the price of the meal, my expectations were higher.

Not 5 stars, but otherwise a good meal and quality service.</Review>
</record></dataset><record>

<userid>111235742658863176800< /userid><Name>Daniel Hartsig< /Name><Time>1352840069653<//Time><rating>3<//rating>< Review>
Zagat must be slipping... apparently a 25 means: salads made from brown, wilted, store-bought pre-prepared mixes that sat in the back of the fridge too long, mediocre wine selections and crab so overcooked you have to chew on it like a strap of leather.  If you want better seafood, go to a Red Lobster.  Scoma's was singularly terrible in that regard.  No complaints about the atmosphere or the waitstaff though, they did a great job.  It was too bad that when they asked me how everything was, the only nice thing I could say was that the bread was great (and it was).</Review>

<Date>1486169270200< /Date><Gmap_id>0x808580fc871ec6ad:0x976bca61020dcc34</Gmap_id>< Text>
Ordered bistro filet, wagyu sirloin cut with smashed potatoes, and raw sliced carrots. Presentation wasn't great. Carrots were right; raw and edible. Smashed potatoes were right and cooked well. The 9 oz filet by no means looked like 9oz it was dished up cut in half. The temperature of the steak was more like medium than what was ordered which was supposed to be medium rare. I have had more flavorful and more tender steaks at a chain restaurant.

The waiter Chris was nice and courteous.<//Text>

<Review>Scoma's is a legacy, but they are just fundamentally being outgrown. Wish they would pare down the menu, update the decor a little bit, and put a little more attention on the waitstaff's skills.

Service was good, appropriately polite and attentive, but kind of clumsy in execution for the intended ambience. E.g. reaching over other guests to serve plates and grate cheese, or forgetting which plate goes where, or just generally awkward interruptions in table conversation and rushed ordering. To be fair, we sat at the bar tables instead of waiting for our reservation.

Food was good but not great. My Bolognese was obviously fresh but the papardelle was sticking and the sauce wasn't much to write home about. Table bread was cold.

I recognize that I'm likely being picky on the details, but based upon the price of the meal, my expectations were higher.

Not 5 stars, but otherwise a good meal and quality service.<//Review><Gmap_id>0x808580fc871ec6ad:0x976bca61020dcc34<//Gmap_id><rate>4<//rate>< time>

<userid>113861163979876786447</userid><name>Todd Hammond< /name><date>1452200789904<//date><rating>4</rating>< text>
Walked in off the street and had about a 15 minute wait to be seated. It was a fairly busy day so there was no place to sit while we waited. They use a texting service to let you know your table is ready, so we just walked around outside.

We started with the fried calamari and it was very good - they cooked it differently then we've ever had it before - big pieces (great dipping sauce too).

After the calamari, we were all actually pretty full so we weren't as hungry for dinner as we would have liked. We had swordfish, shrimp in egg batter and ahi. All were cooked well and tasted good, but not amazing.

Great views from the restaurant, super service, will come back to try the clam chowder!</text>

<review>Skip this place. It was recommended to us and we went to this classic and long-established restaurant. A short wait at the bar and we were eating. The service from Jose was friendly, but the food was at best average, and the prices are high ($110 (incl tip) for dinner for 2, no apps or dessert and 2 beer/wine each). The fresh wild salmon was utterly unremarkable, slightly overcooked and with little flavor (I could have easily done better at home any number of ways), and the pasta with sausage was OK but overwhelmed by black olives. Perhaps other things on the menu are better, but at these prices I can't see coming back to eat my way through the menu to find something better than average. Spend your money elsewhere.

<rate>2< /rate><review>This is an "Old School" Italian Seafood Restaurant.....perfect.....our two most favorite foods (Italian and Seafood) and we LOVE anything "Old School."
Upon entering.....you immediately get the 60's vibe.  We went for My 50th Birthday lunch....so had every intention of hanging for a bit with a bottle of wine and of course some Birthday dessert.....all those things that really help to run up the bill....and we didn't care one bit. We were seated in the back upper level. The dining room was not very big and they made sure to seat everyone in one section so it was hard to have any real conversation. We ordered a cocktail while looking over the menu. We both decided on Seafood. My husband ordered the Salmon and I ordered the Dungeness Crab Salad, with a bottle of wine to come w/the meal. Our lunches were brought to the table and as soon as the server walked away, my husband looked at his fish and said "this doesn't look good"  I looked at the fish and could see what he was talking about.....it looked so dried out. He took a few bites and it was awful. My salad was ok....it was supposed to be shelled crab. Of course every bite I took, I had to pull shell out of my mouth. Shelled=Means no shell or cartilage. I can understand a bite or two w/shell but this was ridiculous. The server forgot the wine and we were so glad.....because we were so unhappy that we just wanted to get out of there.  We couldn't believe this is what was served for the price. Our bill was was $125......before tip.  We didn't bother to send the food back because we figured everything was going to come out just as bad.  So totally disappointed! I think the chef needs more training or they need to have better quality control. Would NEVER recommend this establishment.<//review><Pictures>None<//Pictures>< Response>

Moreover, FV Pioneer has no claim to operate retail fish sales on property that Scoma‚Äôs leases.\nScoma‚Äôs voluntarily agreed to allow a portion of their leasehold to be temporarily used since 2017 without costs to FV Pioneer for retail fish sales as a good neighbor supporting local fishers. Otherwise, the FV Pioneer would not have been able to operate a fish retail business without the cooperation of Scoma‚Äôs and the Port.\nScoma‚Äôs can no longer accommodate FV Pioneer retail fish sales on its property due to health and social distancing guidelines. The City has offered new opportunities for restaurants, whose doors have been shuttered for the past three months, to operate outdoor dining in efforts to stem the financial hardship that the virus has caused on the restaurant industry.\nScoma‚Äôs and FV Pioneer attempted to work together to find a mutually beneficial solution. As no solution has presented itself, the Port must support Scoma‚Äôs claims to use the property they are leasing from the Port. Thus, the FV Pioneer can berth there but it may no longer make retail sales.\n\nThank you for your interest and please contact the Port of San Francisco if you have any questions regarding this situation."}</Resp>

The service is classic, good and attentive.
Can be recommended if you can afford it.
